Prior art is any evidence that your invention is already Prior art does not need to exist physically or be commercially It is enough that someone, somewhere, sometime previously has described and made something that contains a use of technology that is very similar to your Prior art can be: An existing product is the most obvious form of prior Any publication Any material available to the public Making available and exhibitions of products agreements Oral disclosures How to conduct a Prior Art Search? The searching involves following steps: Review the Patent: Review the patent you are researching and gain a detailed understanding of the technology involved as well as any key features of the You t and free) that you can use to search for prior art Maintain a Search Log: Keep a search log to record your previous search parameters and results Mapping the Claims: Once you have narrowed your search results compare each of the claims of the patent to the prior art Patentability Novelty Search Screen inventions at an early stage to reduce your prosecution costs A quick novelty check, prior to Nashville Banner the Nashville Banner On , , Gannett bought and immediately shut down the Nashville Banner . Since that day, the number of journalists in Nashville has been cut by more than , even as the city and surrounding area have enjoyed explosive It‚Äôs time to do So in , Nashville Banner will as a , nonprofit, civic news We hope to finish initial fundraising in so that we may begin publishing online early next Some questions you might have ‚Ä¶ What news will the Banner cover? At its core, we will cover the kind of news that will help you make decisions when you step into a voting How are our taxes being spent? Who are the people, institutions, companies and organizations that affect our lives? Are the persons in power accountable for the decisions they are making? We believe that the digital age has given us more and more commentary about the news, but less and less actual We expect to begin with reporters focused on Metro government, the courts, Capitol Hill and state government, education, business, and criminal We will add coverage areas over time, but the biggest need right now is for civic Why does the Banner need to raise money? Quality local news is It requires hiring good people and giving them the time and resources to do their We are raising a few years worth of startup capital in order to give us the runway necessary to build a sustainable If you are interested and have the ability to help us reach our goal, email us at How will it work? The Banner will be published by Nashville Public Media, , a Tennessee NPM has submitted an application to the IRS for recognition as an organization exempt from tax under Section (c)(3). The Community Foundation of Middle Tennessee, a supporter of the Banner and of nonprofit journalism in Nashville, has set up the Banner Fund to financially support the Banner‚Äôs mission and allow the public to Contributions to the Banner Fund are deductible for tax Once recognized under Section (c)(3), contributions directly to Nashville Public Media and the Banner will be eligible for deduction as The Banner will be published online and will be an independent, news source about issues that affect Nashville and We will offer uniquely Nashville newsletters, podcasts and videos to augment the Banner‚Äôs article To help support the mission of the Banner, memberships will be offered that will include priority access to events and early access to limited Persons, companies, or other charitable organizations that are interested in supporting the Banner‚Äôs mission may contact us at Who is behind the Nashville Banner ? Steve Cavendish is the president and A veteran of newspapers including the Chicago Tribune and The Washington Post , Steve returned to Nashville in and edited both The City Paper and Nashville Scene . Demetria Kalodimos is the executive She is a household name in Nashville, having anchored and reported news for years at the city‚Äôs first television station, She has won many of the most prestigious awards in broadcast journalism and has produced documentaries and programs for the festival circuit and nationally on What can I do? Give us your email As we get closer to launch, we will let you know about events, staff additions and how you can become a Share your email with us Email Address First Name Last Name Thank you, Steve and Demetria Copyright ¬© Nashville Banner

Since the crisis, physicians have been wondering whether they can treat patients anywhere in the Because telehealth lets you connect with patients in any location they have an internet connection, a doctor might as easily see a patient the across the country as across On March , for instance, the federal government waived all state licensure requirements for physicians for purposes of Medicare and Medicaid reimbursement during the Previously, one of the expectations for physicians participating in Medicare was that they have a state license in the state they are furnishing Now, with telehealth, a physician can perform and bill for Medicare or Medicaid services anywhere across the country, even if he or she doesn‚Äôt have a license in that However, states still need to take similar action to permit physicians to practice in their state without a Since states are responsible for actually licensing doctors according to their particular medical board rules, a federal waiver does not affect their requirements for So far, a number of states have in one way or another waived their requirements that a physician hold a license in their state if the physician holds a license in another California and Florida, for instance, will permit any licensed physician to perform services in their states Other states, like Texas and North Carolina, have not gone that far, but have set up expedited licensing processes for physicians looking to assist via telehealth during the When a state does this, not only is the service able to be covered by Medicare and other payors, but the physician is better protected from any allegation that he or she is practicing medicine without a Better still, the Interstate Medical Licensure Compact (IMLC) allows doctors in a participating state to quickly obtain licenses from all other member states (currently at states). Using these three methods together (licensure waivers, temporary emergency licenses, and the IMLC process), physicians can obtain licensure in nearly the entire country on a rapid The federal government is strongly encouraging states to adopt a temporary licensure waiver or set up expedited processing for In a letter sent to all governors, the Department of Health and Human Services asked all states to temporarily suspend their licensing requirements if a physician was licensed in another While this is not mandatory, many have taken this Notably, the guidelines for licensure are changing daily, particularly as states start to face higher incidents of diagnoses and are needing to react to the spike in demand for healthcare It is important to check the current status of waivers and tempor

Organizer Q&A: Feeling So Real ‚Äì How Junction2 Organizers Create Community In The Digital Space ‚Äì Festival Advisor Sign Up Sign Up Organizer Q&A Feeling So Real ‚Äì How Junction2 Organizers Create Community In The Digital Space Bella Bagshaw bella4x4 Jan 8, min read Return to all articles In one fell swoop, the pandemic stripped music lovers, industry professionals and artists of that sense of community festivals have the singular power to Thankfully, Junction 2 has resolved to bring a bit of those simple joys The team behind London‚Äôs annual techno and electronic festival was heading into what would‚Äôve been its sixth and most year when COVID catastrophe Rather than throw a year‚Äôs worth of efforts to the wayside, they‚Äôll come to viewers with Connections : the J2 team‚Äôs strictly digital and highly interactive new production this Saturday, In place of Junction 2‚Äôs lauded, paradoxical homefront at Boston Manor Park‚Äîwhere lush streams and woodlands wind beneath a barebones highway overpass‚ÄîConnections will stream live from three watershed cities in electronic music‚Äôs prolific history: London, Detroit, and Created by ravers for ravers, the event offers a bit of happenstance that‚Äôs missing in a lot of music streaming Connections allows attendees to anonymously communicate with one another throughout the It also resurrects a bit of the tactile with its ‚Äúblack box service,‚Äù a menagerie of drinks, mixers and recipes which festivalgoers can purchase ahead of the show and enjoy on the day of the With virtual reality, gaming and a hell of a techno selection, Connections is poised to hold electronic aficionados over through this flummoxing festival Festival Advisor sat down with Junction 2 Connections Will Harold and Paul Jack to hear what it took to shift gears and plan the digital event as well as their plans for the future, and how they‚Äôll create a sense of occasion You can register for the Junction2 Connections virtual event on their website . Give a bit of background on the festival‚Äôs origins for our readers Harold: Junction 2 is a techno and electronic music festival born out of our passion for It‚Äôs grown from a , event, and it‚Äôs in a pretty unique location under a large motorway The stage is an unusual It‚Äôs a mixture of this stark, industrial concrete bridge that runs through this really beautiful Underneath, you‚Äôve got meandering rivers, streams and I think there‚Äôs a real contrast that‚Äôs made the It would‚Äôve been our fifth It‚Äôs grown to ,000 people, and hopefully one of the most exciting electronic music lineups in [England] or It‚Äôs finally found a place on the world stage‚Äîone that people want to play and come Jack: It‚Äôs growing It was ,000 people when it launched, and in the course of four years, it‚Äôs gone to ,000, expanding from one to two days in its third This year was the most successful year we were going to The talent was excited, a slightly different audience was introduced to the event by broadening the musical We were heading for a We‚Äôre understandably disappointed for it not to It‚Äôs something we really looked forward to all year round‚Äîbeing a culmination of all the work we put in over the last two It still feels very The digital event was born out of the event not taking When we did [the digital event] in July the first time around, the success of that followed up with a winter virtual edition, which is the one we‚Äôre leading into this Growing that quickly is a fantastic position to be in, which I‚Äôm sure comes with its own set of What‚Äôs unique to throwing a event? Jack: Easy: We‚Äôd never done it It‚Äôs something me and Will were Not having something to mark the occasion seemed kinda We had to learn from scratch how to do It‚Äôs one thing putting on livestream of It‚Äôs another thing to actually engineer ‚Ä¶ and recreate a feeling of energy, experience, exploration - and curation of Not having one channel but multiple That‚Äôs why people go to It was Our way of doing it refined as we We were expecting reasonable numbers, but the show on the day delivered over million [It] was gobsmacking to see that many people tuning into A vast number came from the US, I think about percent of the It was countries from different time The chatter online was amazing to see, people logging online at 5 o‚Äôclock in the morning in their Because it was presented as live, it was very important for us to run it at fixed times rather than separate times for different It is one event, rather than a in different It was a real learning experience, and all those learnings we‚Äôve taken away to do this One of the things we realized is the digital landscape is incredibly There‚Äôs so much stuff out there, people just putting on left, right and center: Because they want to, Because they feel the need A lot of it is clogging up You need to give things a purpose, which is why we‚Äôve done less and focused on why we‚Äôre doing We came up with a concept - techno - and we‚Äôre gonna root it in key cities that represent our Harold: Underground electronic music has
